<td>
<a name="PQN340697"></a>
<br>
<span class="headline">Tech Info (Trivia)</span><br>
<span class="byline">12/15/01, 10:45 PST | <a href="mailto:Stryker@planeteq.com">Stryker</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem">I saw this post on <a href="http://www.everlore.com" target="_top">EverLore</a> and thought it would be good to share with you guys. It's a post from "Zackron":<blockquote><p>
How many computers does it take to run EverQuest?<p>

That is an interesting question I got in the mail not that long ago. Unforatunatly the Video Card / Win95 stuff got in the way of me being able to post about it right away...<p>

If you ask any seasoned EverQuest player, they sould be able to tell you that there are currently 41 Servers that make up everquest that one can select to play on (or you can count them from the official everquest site..). However, I single computer can not run an entire server on it's own... It takes many "HELPER" or "ZONE" servers to assist in running the game.<p.

As of the Luclin release, all game servers now have a total of 33 of these zone servers. That means that each Zone server holds from 3 to 6 physical game zones (depending on how big the zone is and how much traffic is in those zones).<p>

When you do some quick math... 41 game servers... 33 helper zone servers per game world server... , and you end up with 1,394 server computers!!! That's alot of computers just to run a single game, and that's not counting the chat or login or patch or other background computers that are needed to make your game play possible...<p>

So, next time you are asking yourself why the server patch time is so long, remember that Verant does not just have to update 41 game servers, but they have to update 1,394+ server computers across multiple internet backbones! That's an accomplishment in itself!</blockquote></span><br><br>
</td>
<td width="10"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=10 height=1 border="0"></td>
</tr>
